    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/continuous-flow-lvad-hemolysis-2p5lpm",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/monte-carlo-uq-hemolysis-runs"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis index validation — absolute threshold comparison",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were computed across all five operating points (4.0–6.0 L/min, 2400–3200 RPM) and evaluated against the absolute clinical hemolysis threshold of 0.005 g/100 L specified in the device submission. Predictions show NIH values ranging from 0.0018 to 0.0041 g/100 L, all below threshold. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (n=500 Latin hypercube samples) yields 95th-percentile NIH of 0.0048 g/100 L, remaining below the clinical limit. The validation team concluded that model predictions are consistent with acceptable hemolysis performance. Uncertainty bounds were propagated from blood viscosity, pump geometry tolerances, and turbulence model coefficients. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model (exponents: alpha=0.785, beta=2.416, C=3.62e-5) was applied uniformly. Agreement with expected physiological ranges was noted as satisfactory. No experimental hemolysis dataset collected at the COU operating conditions was available for direct comparison at the time of assessment; the validation result is therefore reported as a threshold-exceedance check without a paired experimental reference."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/secondary-comparator-mismatched",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary validation — continuous-flow LVAD hemolysis dataset comparison",
      "description": "To further substantiate model credibility, CFD predictions were compared against the continuous-flow LVAD hemolysis dataset of Taskin et al. (2012), which reports in-vitro NIH measurements for a geometrically similar centrifugal pump at 2.5 L/min and 2200 RPM using bovine blood in a recirculating loop. CFD predictions at the nearest available operating point (4.0 L/min, 2400 RPM) were scaled to the Taskin flow condition via flow-similarity arguments, yielding a predicted NIH of 0.0022 g/100 L against the reported experimental value of 0.0019 g/100 L — a 15.8% relative error, deemed acceptable. The validation team noted that the Taskin dataset provides a well-characterized experimental reference with documented measurement uncertainty (±8%) and controlled hematocrit (35%). The geometric similarity between the FDA generic centrifugal pump and the Taskin test article was described as sufficient to support cross-comparison. The team concluded that CFD predictive accuracy is adequately demonstrated for the hemolysis quantity of interest. The applicability of this comparison to VAD operating conditions at 4.0–6.0 L/min was not separately examined; the 2.5 L/min reference condition was treated as representative without qualification of the flow-regime transition that occurs above 3.5 L/min where secondary recirculation zones substantially alter shear stress distributions and hemolysis accumulation pathways.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/continuous-flow-lvad-hemolysis-2p5lpm"
    }
  ],
